<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the Doppler effect?", answer: "The Doppler effect is the change in frequency (or wavelength) of a wave as the source and observer move relative to each other. When they approach, the observed frequency is higher (blueshift); when they move apart, it is lower (redshift). For sound, the formula is f' = f * (v +/- v_observer) / (v -/+ v_source), where v is the speed of sound, f is the source frequency, v_source is the source speed, and v_observer is the observer speed. The effect was proposed by Austrian physicist Christian Doppler in 1842." },
  { question: "Why does a siren sound higher as it approaches?", answer: "As an ambulance approaches, each successive sound wave is emitted from a position closer to you, effectively compressing the wavelengths. This compression increases the frequency you hear, making the pitch sound higher. Once the ambulance passes and moves away, each wave is emitted from farther away, stretching the wavelengths and lowering the frequency. The actual frequency emitted by the siren does not change — only the frequency perceived by the observer changes due to relative motion." },
  { question: "Does the Doppler effect apply to light?", answer: "Yes, the Doppler effect applies to all waves, including light. For light, the relativistic Doppler formula must be used because light travels at a constant speed regardless of the source or observer motion. Astronomical redshift (light shifted to lower frequencies from receding galaxies) provided key evidence for the expanding universe. Police radar guns and hospital blood flow monitors also use the Doppler effect with electromagnetic waves." },
  { question: "What happens when the source reaches the speed of sound?", answer: "When a source moves at exactly the speed of sound (Mach 1), all the sound waves pile up at the same point, creating a shock wave known as a sonic boom. The Doppler formula's denominator becomes zero, meaning the observed frequency theoretically goes to infinity. In reality, a sharp pressure discontinuity forms. At supersonic speeds (above Mach 1), the source outruns its own sound waves and a Mach cone forms, with the cone angle depending on the ratio of sound speed to source speed." },
  { question: "What is the difference between blueshift and redshift?", answer: "Blueshift refers to an increase in observed frequency (decrease in wavelength) when the source and observer approach each other. The term comes from the blue end of the visible light spectrum having higher frequencies. Redshift is the opposite — a decrease in frequency (increase in wavelength) when they move apart. Though named after light colors, these terms are used for all waves. Cosmological redshift of distant galaxies indicates the expansion of the universe." }
]) %>

